  "prompt": "Can we use 'the' before the name of any country other than Netherlands?",
  "response": "In English, the use of the definite article \"the\" before the name of a country is generally uncommon, but there are a few exceptions. Here are some guidelines:\n\n### Specific Cases Where \"The\" is Used:\n1. **Countries with Plural Names**:\n   - **The Philippines** (because \"Philippines\" is plural)\n   - **The Bahamas** (because \"Bahamas\" is plural)\n   - **The Maldives** (because \"Maldives\" is plural)\n\n2. **Countries with Names That Include a Common Noun**:\n   - **The United States** (includes \"States,\" a common noun)\n   - **The United Kingdom** (includes \"Kingdom,\" a common noun)\n   - **The Czech Republic** (includes \"Republic,\" a common noun)\n\n3. **Historical or Contextual Usage**:\n   - **The Gambia** (officially includes \"The\" in its name)\n   - **The Congo** (refers to the region or river)\n\n### Examples Where \"The\" is Generally Not Used:\n- Most country names **do not** take \"the\":\n  - France, Germany, Japan, Brazil, India, etc.\n\n### Special Note on \"The Netherlands\":\n- The Netherlands is an exception because its name historically refers to \"the low lands,\" hence the definite article \"the\" is always used.\n\n### Summary:\nYou can use \"the\" before a country name **only if**:\n- The name is plural (e.g., The Philippines).\n- The name includes a common noun (e.g., The United States).\n- It is officially or historically part",
